# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Brooklyn baseball club was formed in 1883 by real estate magnate and baseball enthusiast Charles Byrne who convinced his brother-in-law Joseph Doyle and casino operator Ferdinand Abell to start the team with him.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Byrne set up a grandstand on fifth avenue and named it Washington Park in honor of George Washington.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The team played in the minor Inter-State Association of Professional Baseball Clubs.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] Doyle became the first manager of the team, which drew 6,000 fans to its first home game on May 12, 1883, against the Trenton team.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] (This was actually the second game the club played in Brooklyn; three days earlier, with Washington Park not yet ready, the Greys beat Harrisburg 7–1 at the Parade Ground.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] It was the only professional match ever held at the ground, with some 2,000 fans in attendance.) The team won the league title after the **Camden Merritt** club disbanded on July 20 and Brooklyn picked up some of its better players.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1883-brooklyn-grays-season] The Grays were invited to join the American Association for the following season.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] The **1884 Baltimore Monumentals** finished with a 58–47 record in the Union Association, finishing in fourth place.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-baltimore-monumentals-season] This was the only season this version of the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1884 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 14th season of the franchise.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-boston-reds-season] The **1884 Boston Reds** finished with a 58–51 record in the Union Association, finishing in fifth place (fourth among teams that played a full schedule).
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-boston-reds-season] This was the only season the team existed, and indeed the only season the Union Association existed.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **1884 Brooklyn Atlantics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] It was the first season in the American Association for the team, and they finished the year in ninth place.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The Brooklyn baseball team had played as the **Brooklyn Grays** in the Interstate Association in 1883, where they won the championship.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season] In 1884, Charles Byrne moved the team into the American Association, renaming them the Atlantics in tribute to the old National Association Brooklyn Atlantics team.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/1884-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1884 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 64–47 record, good for third place in the National League.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] The **1884 Chicago Browns/Pittsburgh Stogies** finished with a 41–50 record (34–39 while in Chicago, 7–11 while in Allegheny City) in the Union Association, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] The team moved from Chicago to Allegheny City (today a part of Pittsburgh's North Shore) after their game of August 22.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] The team folded completely after their game of September 18, which was about a month before the 1884 season was scheduled to be over.
[src:1884-brooklyn-atlantics-season/pittsburgh-stogies-season] With the Wilmington Quicksteps also having folded on September 21, and with about a dozen games remaining to be played, for the final games of the season the two defunct teams were replaced by teams from Milwaukee and St.
